        "body": "Yeah I think this could be a good feature and it could be built using blockwise, but it might take a little thought to get right. I tried a naive approach and it didn't do quite the right thing.\r\n\r\n```python\r\nimport pandas as pd\r\nimport dask.dataframe as dd\r\n\r\ndf = pd.DataFrame(data={'col1': [1, 2, 4, 5], 'col2': [3, 4, 6, 9]})\r\nddf = dd.from_pandas(df, 2)\r\nddf.map_partitions(lambda df: df.transpose(), enforce_metadata=False).compute()\r\n```\r\n```python\r\n        0    1    2    3\r\ncol1  1.0  2.0  NaN  NaN\r\ncol2  3.0  4.0  NaN  NaN\r\ncol1  NaN  NaN  4.0  5.0\r\ncol2  NaN  NaN  6.0  9.0\r\n```\r\n\r\nI'll just also say that since dataframe partitions the data along the index, the data would have to be entirely repartitioned if you want to know the divisions (range of each partition).",
